 **Verification is the quality gate.** Run the check command if one exists. Use the verifier agent for intelligent verification. If checks pass, your work is presumed correct. If they fail, your work is not done.
 
+**Visual self-verification.** When the project is a visual surface (React, Vue, Vite, Next, etc.), four sensors are available to you and should be consulted after any UI-affecting change:
+
+- `playwright` — launches Chromium and screenshots the running dev server. The dev-server port is read from `shape.md` `## Runtime` section (e.g. `- **Dev server port:** 5173`); if absent, 5173, 3000, 8080, and 4321 are probed in order. The screenshot is written under the build's `sensors/` directory.
+- `vision` — sends the most recent screenshot through Claude vision (the same Claude CLI subprocess path used elsewhere) and returns a structured description plus any regressions it notices.
+- `a11y` — injects axe-core into the rendered page via `page.addScriptTag({ path: require.resolve('axe-core') })` and reports WCAG violations. No external network requests.
+- `contrast` — scores design-token hex pairs via `wcag-contrast` and flags any pair below WCAG AA (4.5:1 normal, 3:1 large).
+
+The pattern: after editing UI code, take a screenshot with `playwright`, run `vision` against the screenshot, and run `a11y` + `contrast` to catch accessibility and design-token regressions. Sensor failures are non-fatal warnings — continue the phase even if a sensor emits a warning. If playwright is unresolvable, `a11y` and `vision` will emit a single warning with an install hint; act on it once and move on.
+
 **Use the Agent tool sparingly.** Do the work yourself. Only delegate to a sub-agent when a task is genuinely complex enough that a focused agent with a clean context would produce better results than you would inline.
 
 **Specialist agents may be available.** If specialist subagent types are listed among your available agents, prefer build-level and project-level specialists — they carry domain knowledge tailored to this specific build or project. Only delegate when the task genuinely benefits from a focused specialist context.
